Chalo is example ko properly step-by-step samajhte hain 👇 — yeh host → container environment variable passing ka concept hai (important 🔥)

🧩 Step 1: Host pe variable set karna
🐧 Ubuntu (Linux / Mac)
export APP_PORT=8080
🪟 PowerShell (Windows)
$env:APP_PORT=8080

👉 Iska matlab:

Tumne apne system (host machine) pe variable banaya
Naam: APP_PORT
Value: 8080
🔍 Check karna
Linux:
echo $APP_PORT
PowerShell:
echo $env:APP_PORT
🧩 Step 2: Docker command
docker run -e APP_PORT=$env:APP_PORT nginx env
docker run -e APP_PORT=$APP_PORT nginx env

Yeh Docker ka command hai

🔑 Main Concept

👉 Tum host ka variable container ke andar pass kar rahe ho

🔍 Breakdown
🧪 Command structure
docker run -e APP_PORT=<value> nginx env
-e → environment variable set karta hai
nginx → Nginx image
env → container ke andar variables print karega
⚡ Difference samjho
🪟 PowerShell
docker run -e APP_PORT=$env:APP_PORT nginx env

👉 $env:APP_PORT = Windows syntax

🐧 Linux / Ubuntu
docker run -e APP_PORT=$APP_PORT nginx env

👉 $APP_PORT = Linux syntax

🔄 Kya ho raha hai internally
Host pe variable set kiya (APP_PORT=8080)
Docker run kiya
-e ke through value pass ki
Container ke andar variable create ho gaya
env command usko print kar raha hai
📤 Output (andar container)
APP_PORT=8080
PATH=...
HOSTNAME=...
🧠 Simple language me

“Host pe jo variable hai, usko Docker container ke andar bhej diya”

🎯 Important Point

❗ Agar host variable set nahi hai:

docker run -e APP_PORT=$APP_PORT nginx env

👉 to container me empty aa sakta hai:

APP_PORT=
🧠 Real-world use
Port config (APP_PORT)
DB credentials
API keys
App settings
🔥 One-line summary

Host variable → -e → Container variable
